AUDIO: 'one. And then really quickly, here\'s the case sampler. You should be already familiar with this if you\'ve been watching my previous Comfy UI tutorials. But anyways, really quickly, the seed is basically the starting point of your'

[22:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image because in theory, there could be almost an infinite number of different images it could generate with this prompt. And then this seed number is just one of the many images. Now, usually you just set the seed to random'

[22:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it doesn\'t matter. But if you set the seed to the same value as before, and you keep all the same settings, then it\'s going to generate the exact same image as before. And then the number of steps is basically how many iterations of denoising you want it to go through'

[22:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'before outputting your final image. So in general, the more steps you have, it\'s going to take longer to run, but you\'re going to get slightly better quality. But at a certain point, if you set it to too many steps, you are going to get diminishing returns. So at that'

[22:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'point, you\'re just wasting compute. Conversely, if you set the step count to too low, like only 10 steps, then it\'s going to run way faster, but at the sacrifice of some quality. And then CFG is like how literally you want the AI to'

[23:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'follow your prompt up here. So a high CFG value would really get it to generate everything you specify very literally, whereas a low CFG value would give it more creativity and it might add'

[23:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some variance to the output. And then the sampler name anduler. These are basically different algorithms you can use to generate your image. Feel free to play around with these. Each one has a slightly different and subtle effect.'

